An airshed is a part of the [[Earth's atmosphere|atmosphere]] that behaves in a coherent way with respect to the dispersion of [[Air pollutants|emissions]]. It typically forms an analytical or management unit. Also: a geographic boundary for air-quality standards.
Alternatively - an airshed is a geographical area where local [[topography]] and [[meteorology]] limit the dispersion of pollutants away from the area.<ref> {{cite web |last=Okrainetz |first=Glen |title=Air Quality Management in British Columbia |url=http://www.bc.lung.ca/association_and_services/documents/02Okrainetz-AirQualityManagementinBC.pdf |publisher=BC Lung Ass'n |accessdate=July 6, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116084811/http://www.bc.lung.ca/association_and_services/documents/02Okrainetz-AirQualityManagementinBC.pdf |archivedate=January 16, 2014 }} </ref>
