{{short description|A technique for ocean bottom sampling}}

{{orphan|date=October 2012}}

'''Ocean dredging''' was an [[oceanography]] technique introduced in the nineteenth century and developed by naturalist [[Edward Forbes]]. He would lay out the [[dredging|dredged]] material on the deck to examine, preserve and study it. The practice was chronicled in a remembrance of Forbes by [[William Jerdan]] in his 1866 book ''Men I Have Known''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Men I Have Known|author=Jerdan, W.|year=1866|location=London|publisher=George Routledge and Sons|url=https://archive.org/details/menihaveknown00jerdgoog}}</ref>

==References==

